Fire has gutted a portion of the Kaduna residence of the prominent Islamic cleric, Sheikh Ahmad Gumi. The incident, which occurred on Saturday, affected an Islamiyya school located inside the compound along Alimi Road in the Kaduna metropolis. Tukur Mamu, the media consultant to Gumi, confirmed the incident through a statement. “This is to confirm a fire outbreak in Sheikh Ahmad Gumi’s residence. While the cause of the fire which lasted for about four hours is yet to be ascertained, we can confirm that no life was lost,” the statement said.   Obi Okonjo wins 150-year kingship battle in Delta     BREAKING: ASUU in final meeting for possible indefinite…     Nigerians decry threat, intimidation, cyberbullying by loan…   “Contrary to media reports, the fire did not affect the second part of the large building where the Sheikh and his family reside. - Advertisement - “For clarity, part of the big edifice, a story building in the main entrance; a female secondary school, Khulitul Banat Girls’ College  which was founded by Gumi, was affected. “The side that was completely destroyed by the fire incident was the upper floor of the girls’ college. The well-equipped laboratory, computer sections (with about 50 computers) and four classrooms all on the upper floor of the building were destroyed by the fire. The source of the fire is not yet known,” he said. An eyewitness told reporters that they suddenly saw a cloud of thick smoke emanating from the building just very close to the gate, forcing neighbours to fetch water to put out the fire. Officials of the Kaduna State Fire Service later rushed to the scene and successfully put out the fire; to prevent it from spreading to the entire compound. SPONSORED